This particular grade military spec armor steel is especially useful to protect structures or vehicles from sniper fire or any form of weapon that will emit the HVPs depending on the threat level, various thicknesses of steel may be required to protect vital organs.

Then shot it with AK 47 50rnds, 5.56 30rnds, endless .357/9mm/45cal, 7.62x54R, .30-06 and a 300 win mag 3 times at 250yards, that did flatten the plate but still no penetration. Not to mention shot at it with a .45 handgun...still no penetration. This will not fail to disappoint as it this is one of the best quality steel out there. Ar500 is target material not to be used as body armor. This body armor with the 2 plates and the vest weighs a total of 12 pounds. I've shot at this multiple times with different rifles and Handguns and it still holds up. You could attach MOLLE gear to this vest such as your Hydration water Carrier, Rifle and Handgun Magazine pouches, Radio pouches, EMT Medical pouches and etc.

It comes complete ready to shoot I have a few handloads for it and 100 rounds of unloaded 460 Rowland brass.  Out of the 460 Rowland barrel you can shoot 45acp, 45 Super or 460 Rowland. You can not shoot 460 Rowland brass in a normal 45acp barrel the brass is 1/16th long then a 45acp case you do use the same 45 acp dies to load 

Check out 460Rowland.com for more info on this load.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Browning FN 1900 - World War II Bring-back WITH documentation
postcontent:
I have a Browning FN 1900 (Brevete SGDG) - .32 auto.  The pistol is matching numbers, the model was produced between 1900 - 1912, so it predates World War I.  

The FN 1900 is actually the first variant of the 'original' Browning pistol, the 1899.  The pistol I have has very little finish left but is all matching on the serial numbers.   The holster is also period correct, Slepmann manufactured.

The bring-back documentation is from 1946 and matches serial numbers with the pistol.  Overall a pretty interesting piece of history.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Teardrop Travel Trailer For Sale
postcontent:
Ultralight teardrop for sale, weighs only 725 lbs. Garage kept, but has logged more than a few miles. Pulls behind my little Toyota just fine. More than light enough to move around with one person pushing on level ground. 

CONDITION
Excellent. No leaks, all gaskets/seals are in great shape. Electrical system is solid and professionally done; I can make modest repairs but I do not work with electrical systems. Frame has no rust and has a good coat of paint. Wheel bearings are well greased. Clear title and registration with permanent plate in Louisiana. Insurance is dirt cheap. No smoking and no pets.

Selling because I am moving in a year or so and can't tow it behind a Uhaul with a car carrier, though it would certainly be interesting to try! Louisiana requires that a notary sign transfer, but there are many title transfer/notary places in town. Located in the New Orleans area and available in that general area for viewing by appointment. Price is firm; there's a lot invested in this thing with the upgrades and upkeep I've done. Similar offerings from commercial manufacturers are considerably more expensive, and this is about what it would cost to do it yourself from scratch.

EXTERIOR
Total length: 10' 6"
Maximum height: 69"
Maximum width at fenders: 69 inches. The lug not covers stick out an extra inch on each side.
Center of gravity/tongue weight is safe and appropriate for length. As with any trailer load distribution is important and easy to tweak. The spare tire could be moved to the roof rack if you want to make big permanent changes, but I find it's easier to move things around in the interior of the cabin.
Lots of ground clearance: frame rides at 18 inches above ground. Trailers with Harbor Freight tires do not have this. Don't get stuck on the road to a campground with crummy toy-sized wheels.
Hi Spec Aluminum 15 " Alloy Wheels with hub covers and matching full size spare mounted on tongue. Plenty of tread on the tires, and they're in good shape. I don't have a tread gauge but the penny measurement is good. Spare has not been driven on, and is brand new, less than a year old. Items can be bungeed or strapped to top of spare. My grill (not included) usually goes there. Buyer could also have a platform welded or bolted on. 
Full size round fenders.
Adjustable height folding side table.  
Exterior trim is well sealed with flexible RV sealant and fastened with Robertson screws under a protective gasket. Gasket is in great shape and has been treated with 3M protectant.
Lil Bear Roof Rack. Removable. Would be perfect with a small cargo carrier mounted. I never got around to it. It's easier to put a mat down to protect the finish and use ratchet straps to hold things down. 
Fantastic Fan, shaded dome with direction switch and three speeds. Moves a heck of a lot of air, low setting is usully sufficient.
Porch light with exterior switch. 
Passenger side door with locking slam latch and deadbolt and sliding window with screen. Additional sliding locking window with screen on driver side. Plenty of ventilation with or without the fan. 
Streamlined LED running, brake, and turn lights. Just tested to ensure good ground and function.
13 gallon water tank with driver side fill port and passenger side dispenser. Multiple ports for changes to existing setup if you want. My work in progress is a simple gravity fill design.
Weathertight 110 power hookup on rear driver side.
Folding front jack with wheel.
Safety reflectors on rear and side.
Experimental curb finder on rear. 

INTERIOR
Lots of interior room for such compact exterior dimensions, particularly headroom. 
Measurements: 41" H x 46.5" W x 80" L. 
35 Amp Hour AGM battery. Enough for three to four days of moderate usage, or two weeks of light usage. Holds a charge while sitting pretty well, but I periodically run and top it off.
Insulated storage/battery compartment with sliding doors at foot of mattress.
Small heater (included) can be plugged into the socket in the cabinet. Not necessary to run it all night; a few minutes in the evening before bed and when waking up are sufficient.
Flip down DVD player with remote, wireless headphones, and game system. Never used it except to listen to radio and watch DVDs but it works. 
CD player/radio with aux headphone input with 4 speaker Pioneer speaker system. Plenty of volume for listening at camp outside if you leave the window screen open . 
Three interior overhead lights: dome, and left and right directional reading lights.
Red interior nighttime light in footwell. Good for not killing your night vision. Ended up using this one most of the time.
Twin cabinets with doors above the footwell. 
Folding cupholders on each side of cabin.
Twin size dual layer foam mattress.
Carpeted headboard.
Finished vinyl wood floor. Looks pretty good. 
RV breaker and fuse panel in footbox: Progressive Dynamics PD4045KA with intelligent charging features, including a quick charge mode. All circuits are run through panel, so the wiring is good. Has room for expansion. 
1 Interior 110 socket and 2 interior 12v DC sockets. Radio, DVD, charging sockets, all lights, fan, and TV will run off battery. 110 socket obviously only runs off a 110 when hooked up.
ACCESSORIES
Folding Stepstool for easy entry.
Popup changing tent: Trekker Fold-A-Privy in like new condition
Heavy duty power cord
Wheel chocks and donut for front wheel
Multiple security locks for hitch pin, ball, door, and axle. Two full sets of keys for all locks.
